      </item> </list> </solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="secfhsst_id245"><title> Lewis notation: Molecules with multiple bonds
      </title>
      <problem id="probfhsst_id247">
      <para id="id140364">Represent the molecule HCN using Lewis notation</para>
      
      </problem>
      <solution id="solfhsst_id251"> <list id="listfhsst_id251" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" class="stepwise">
      <item> <label> For each atom, determine the number of valence electrons that the atom has from its electron configuration. </label>
      <para id="id140394">The electron configuration of hydrogen is 1s<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msup></m:math>, the electron configuration of nitrogen is 1s<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:math> 2s<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:math> 2p<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:msup></m:math> and for carbon is 1s<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:math> 2s<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:math> 2p<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:math>. This means that hydrogen has one valence electron which is unpaired, carbon has four valence electrons, all of which are unpaired, and nitrogen has five valence electrons, three of which are unpaired.</para>
