<section id="secfhsst_id312"><title>
      Dative covalent bonds
      </title>
      <para id="id140800">A <emphasis effect="bold">dative covalent bond</emphasis> (also known as a coordinate covalent bond) is a description of covalent bonding between two atoms in which both electrons shared in the bond come from the same atom. This happens when a Lewis base (an electron donor) donates a pair of electrons to a Lewis acid (an electron acceptor). Lewis acids and bases will be discussed in <link target-id=""/> in chapter <link target-id=""/>.</para>
      <para id="id140819">One example of a molecule that contains a dative covalent bond is the ammonium ion (NH<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msubsup><m:mrow/><m:mrow><m:mn>4</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mo>+</m:mo></m:msubsup></m:math>) shown in the figure below. The hydrogen ion H<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mo>+</m:mo></m:msup></m:math> does not contain any electrons, and therefore the electrons that are in the bond that forms between this ion and the nitrogen atom, come only from the nitrogen.</para>
      <para id="id140858">
        <figure id="id140861">
          <media id="id140861_media" alt="">
            <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CG11C1_017.png" id="id140861_onlineimage" width="252"><!-- NOTE: attribute width changes image size online (pixels). original width is 252. --></image>
            <image mime-type="application/postscript" for="pdf" src="../../media/CG11C1_017.eps" id="id140861_printimage"/>
          </media>
        </figure>
      </para>
      
</section>
